1. Define the two input strings as two arrays of characters.
2. Initialize two pointers, one for each string, at the first character of each string.
3. Compare the characters of the two pointers. If the characters match, increment a counter. If the characters do not match, choose the smaller pointer and move it forward.
4. Repeat steps 3 and 4 until the end of one or both strings is reached.
5. Return the value of the counter as the LCS.

Here is the code in Java:
```java
public class LCS {
    public static int lcs(String s1, String s2) {
        int m = s1.length();
        int n = s2.length();
        int[] dp = new int[m + 1];
        for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
            dp[i] = new int[n + 1];
            for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
                dp[i][j] = 0;
            }
        }
        for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
                if (s1.charAt(i - 1) == s2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[m][n];
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s1 = "ABCDGH";
        String s2 = "AEDFHR";
        int lcs = lcs(s1, s2);
        System.out.println("LCS: " + lcs);
    }
}
